name: Billingham Library and Customer Service Centre
notes: This new library building replaces the two branches which served Billingham - one close by in the town centre (Rosebery Library) and one in the older part of the community about a mile away.  Both were closed in December 2014 and the new building opened in January 2015.  The library is co-located with a Council Customer Contact Centre and with Billingham Town Council.

name: Egglescliffe Library
notes: This library is currently under Review and is proposed for closure during 2016/2017.  The library at Yarm is less than a mile away and we already provide housebound and mobile library services in this area.  Yarm Library is currently under refurbishment as a "town centre hub library" and will re-open on September 5th 2016.

name: Fairfield Library
notes: This library is currently under Review and is proposed for closure if a co-location opportunity cannot be found.  The library is currently under discussion as a possible site for a nursery unit who may share the building with a reduced size branch library facility.  We already provide housebound and mobile library services in the wards surrounding this library which is not designated as one of our main "town centre hubs".

name: Ingleby Barwick Library
address: Ingleby Barwick Community Campus, Blair Avenue, Ingleby Barwick
notes: This library will be replaced with a new building co-located with a Leisure Centre adjacent to the current Secondary Academy site in 2018.  The library will be significantly larger and will accommodate access to Customer Services in addition to the range of leisure and fitness facilities planned for the building.

name: Ragworth Neighbourhood Centre Library
address: Ragworth Neighbourhood Centre St John's Way, Ragworth, Stockton-on-Tees.
notes: This was a very small unstaffed library co-located in a neighbourhood building and administered by the centre staff with support from Norton Library. Due to a review of buildings and delivery methods, this centre was transferred to a non profit making company who are unable to support the library in its current state. Issue levels and visits were minimal and the branch has been withdrawn in August 2016.

name: Roseworth Library (Redhill Children's Centre)
address: Redhill Children's Centre, Redhill Rd., Roseworth, Stockton-on-Tees
notes: Roseworth Library relocated in 2014 following our last Library Service review to be co-located with a Children's Centre.  The library occupies four spaces which have been completely refurbished with new equipment and library shelving.  This library is designated as a "branch library" and also share the site with the Public Health Information resource, currently run by the public library service but funded by Public Health.  The investment in this library exceeded £50K

name: Stockton Central Library and Customer Service Centre
notes: Stockton Central Library was refurbished in 2011 when it was closed for several months for a complete re-modelling and refit of the building.  The new library incorporates the largest of the Council's Customer Contact Centres as well as a publicly available meeting space and small gallery area.  The main areas of the library are split into a separate, flexible adult and children's lending space, dedicated information and local history library and family history centre.  The library was opened in 1967 and the original structure has been enhanced by the alterations and re-modelling.  This service point is designated as one of our "town centre hub" libraries. This library's refurbishment was in excess of £50K

name: Thornaby Library, Gilmour Street (Riverbank Children's Centre)
notes: Thornaby Library (Westbury Street) was relocated from its stand alone building in 2014 to be co-located with a Children's Centre in neary Gilmour Street.  The branch was completely refurbished and a new space created for it to operate as the entrance to the Children's Centre building.  The Children's Centre is run by an external organisation. Investment in Thornaby Library exceeded £50K

name: Yarm Library
notes: Yarm Library is currently closed for refurbishment and will re-open to the public on September 5th.  The library shelving has been removed and replaced and building work has taken place to provide new facilities and a small branch of Newcastle Building Society who will operate from the library in partnership.  Yarm Library is designated as one of our six "town centre hub" libraries.  Yarm's refurbishment project exceeds £50K
